As Amy wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/26/2004 at 14:14:29 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>A company that sells newspaper subscriptions has 200 customers at the 
>beginning of the year (Jan. 1).  Assume that the company loses no 
>customers and that each customer pays a monthly fee.  The company 
>needs to have 500 accounts (i.e. customers) by the end of the year to 
>meet revenue goals.  If the company is able to acquire customers at 
>the same constant growth rate during Jan-March and Sept-Dec (months 
>of slow growth) but at a different constant growth rate during April-
>August (the busy season), what growth rate is needed in the busy and 
>slow seasons to reach the revenue goals?
>
>[Difficulty]
>I'm having difficulty determining how to set this up as an algebra 
>problem.
>
>[Thoughts]
>There are 2 growth rates, x and y.  x for the busy season, y for the 
>slow season.  
>
>500=200x +x(200x)+ x(x(200x)).........

Hello Amy,

I presume that the growth rates x and y will be so many new accounts per month.  So

500 = 200 + 7*x + 5*y

So,

300 = 7x+5y.

This is a Diophantine Equation, but  I'll guess that they want you to guess.  I know at least 
one solution x and y integral.

